<module topic='1' html='module3' id-text='3' id='uid12'><head>Identification and déconvolution</head>
<p>Let us first introduce the subject of Identification in some generality.
Let us turn to work of the Apics Team<note id-text='1' id='uid13' place='foot'>and of the former
MIAOU-project</note> can be partly recast from the data.</p>
<p>We shall explain in more detail the above steps in the sub-paragraphs
to come.</p>
<div2 id-text='1' id='uid14'><head>Analytic approximation of incomplete boundary data</head>
<participants><pers prenom='Laurent' nom='Baratchart'/>
<pers prenom='José' nom='Grimm'/>
<pers prenom='Juliette' nom='Leblond'/>
<pers prenom='Jean-Paul' nom='Marmorat'>CMA, École des Mines</pers>
<pers prenom='Jonathan' nom='Partington'/>
<pers prenom='Fabien' nom='Seyfert'/>
</participants>
<keywords>
<term>meromorphic approximation</term>
<term>frequency-domain identification</term>
<term>extremal problems</term>
</keywords><p>A prototypical Problem is:</p>
<p><hi rend='slanted'>(<formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mi>P</mi></math></formula>)  Let <formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><mi>p</mi><mo>&ge;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></math></formula>, <formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><mi>N</mi><mo>&ge;</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></math></formula>, <formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mi>K</mi></math></formula> be an arc of the unit circle <formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mi>T</mi></math></formula>,
<formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo>&Element;</mo><msup><mi>L</mi> <mi>p</mi> </msup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>K</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow></math></formula>, <formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><mi>&psi;</mi><mo>&Element;</mo><msup><mi>L</mi> <mi>p</mi> </msup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>T</mi><mo>&setminus;</mo><mi>K</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow></math></formula> and <formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><mi>M</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></math></formula>;
find a function <formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><mi>g</mi><mo>&Element;</mo><msup><mi>H</mi> <mi>p</mi> </msup><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>R</mi> <mi>N</mi> </msub></mrow></math></formula> such that
<formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><msub><mrow><mo>&parallel;</mo><mi>g</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>&psi;</mi><mo>&parallel;</mo></mrow> <mrow><msup><mi>L</mi> <mi>p</mi> </msup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>T</mi><mo>&setminus;</mo><mi>K</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow> </msub><mo>&le;</mo><mi>M</mi></mrow></math></formula> and such that <formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><mi>g</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>f</mi></mrow></math></formula>
is of minimal norm in <formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><msup><mi>L</mi> <mi>p</mi> </msup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>K</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow></math></formula> under this constraint.</hi></p>
<p>In order to impose pointwise constraints in the frequency domain
one may wish to express
the gauge constraint on <formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><mi>T</mi><mo>&setminus;</mo><mi>K</mi></mrow></math></formula> in a more subtle manner, depending on
the frequency:</p>
<p><hi rend='slanted'>(<formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><msup><mi>P</mi> <mo>&apos;</mo> </msup></math></formula>)  Let <formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><mi>p</mi><mo>&ge;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></math></formula>, <formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><mi>N</mi><mo>&ge;</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></math></formula>, <formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mi>K</mi></math></formula> be an arc of the unit circle
<formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mi>T</mi></math></formula>, <formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo>&Element;</mo><msup><mi>L</mi> <mi>p</mi> </msup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>K</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow></math></formula>, <formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><mi>&psi;</mi><mo>&Element;</mo><msup><mi>L</mi> <mi>p</mi> </msup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>T</mi><mo>&setminus;</mo><mi>K</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow></math></formula> and
<formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><mi>M</mi><mo>&Element;</mo><msup><mi>L</mi> <mi>p</mi> </msup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>T</mi><mo>&setminus;</mo><mi>K</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow></math></formula>;
find a function
<formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><mi>g</mi><mo>&Element;</mo><msup><mi>H</mi> <mi>p</mi> </msup><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>R</mi> <mi>N</mi> </msub></mrow></math></formula> such that <formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><mo>|</mo><mi>g</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>&psi;</mi><mo>|</mo><mo>&le;</mo><mi>M</mi></mrow></math></formula> a.e. on
<formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><mi>T</mi><mo>&setminus;</mo><mi>K</mi></mrow></math></formula> and such that <formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><mi>g</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>f</mi></mrow></math></formula> is of minimal norm in
<formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><msup><mi>L</mi> <mi>p</mi> </msup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>K</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow></math></formula> under this constraint.</hi></p>
<p>Deeply linked with Problem <formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>P</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></math></formula>, is the following completion Problem:</p>
<p><hi rend='slanted'>(<formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><msup><mi>P</mi> <mrow><mo>&apos;</mo><mo>&apos;</mo></mrow> </msup></math></formula>)  Let
<formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><mi>p</mi><mo>&ge;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></math></formula>, <formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><mi>N</mi><mo>&ge;</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></math></formula>, <formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mi>K</mi></math></formula> an arc of the unit circle <formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mi>T</mi></math></formula>,
<formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo>&Element;</mo><msup><mi>L</mi> <mi>p</mi> </msup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>K</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow></math></formula>, <formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><mi>&psi;</mi><mo>&Element;</mo><msup><mi>L</mi> <mi>p</mi> </msup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>T</mi><mo>&setminus;</mo><mi>K</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow></math></formula> and
<formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><mi>M</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></math></formula>; find a function
<formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><mi>h</mi><mo>&Element;</mo><msup><mi>L</mi> <mi>p</mi> </msup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>T</mi><mo>&setminus;</mo><mi>K</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow></math></formula> such that
<formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><msub><mrow><mo>&parallel;</mo><mi>h</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>&psi;</mi><mo>&parallel;</mo></mrow> <mrow><msup><mi>L</mi> <mi>p</mi> </msup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>T</mi><mo>&setminus;</mo><mi>K</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow> </msub><mo>&le;</mo><mi>M</mi></mrow></math></formula>, and such that the distance to
<formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><msup><mi>H</mi> <mi>p</mi> </msup><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>R</mi> <mi>N</mi> </msub></mrow></math></formula> of the concatenated function <formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo>&vee;</mo><mi>h</mi></mrow></math></formula>
is minimal in <formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><msup><mi>L</mi> <mi>p</mi> </msup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>T</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow></math></formula> under this constraint.</hi></p>
<p>A version of this problem where the constraint depends on the frequency is:</p>
<p><hi rend='slanted'>(<formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><msup><mi>P</mi> <mrow><mo>&apos;</mo><mo>&apos;</mo><mo>&apos;</mo></mrow> </msup></math></formula>)  Let <formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><mi>p</mi><mo>&ge;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></math></formula>,
<formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><mi>N</mi><mo>&ge;</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></math></formula>, <formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mi>K</mi></math></formula> an arc the unit circle <formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mi>T</mi></math></formula>, <formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo>&Element;</mo><msup><mi>L</mi> <mi>p</mi> </msup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>K</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow></math></formula>,
<formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><mi>&psi;</mi><mo>&Element;</mo><msup><mi>L</mi> <mi>p</mi> </msup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>T</mi><mo>&setminus;</mo><mi>K</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow></math></formula> and
<formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><mi>M</mi><mo>&Element;</mo><msup><mi>L</mi> <mi>p</mi> </msup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>T</mi><mo>&setminus;</mo><mi>K</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow></math></formula>; find a function <formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><mi>h</mi><mo>&Element;</mo><msup><mi>L</mi> <mi>p</mi> </msup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>T</mi><mo>&setminus;</mo><mi>K</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow></math></formula> such that
<formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><mo>|</mo><mi>h</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>&psi;</mi><mo>|</mo><mo>&le;</mo><mi>M</mi></mrow></math></formula> a.e. on <formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><mi>T</mi><mo>&setminus;</mo><mi>K</mi></mrow></math></formula>, and such that the distance to
<formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><msup><mi>H</mi> <mi>p</mi> </msup><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>R</mi> <mi>N</mi> </msub></mrow></math></formula> of the concatenated function <formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo>&vee;</mo><mi>h</mi></mrow></math></formula>
is minimal in <formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><msup><mi>L</mi> <mi>p</mi> </msup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>T</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow></math></formula> under this constraint.</hi></p>
<p>Let us mention that Problem <formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><mo>(</mo><msup><mi>P</mi> <mrow><mo>&apos;</mo><mo>&apos;</mo></mrow> </msup><mo>)</mo></mrow></math></formula> reduces to Problem
<formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>P</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></math></formula> that in turn reduces, although implicitly,
to an extremal Problem without
constraint, (i.e., a Problem of type <formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>P</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></math></formula> where <formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><mi>K</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>T</mi></mrow></math></formula>) that is
denoted conventionally by <formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><mo>(</mo><msub><mi>P</mi> <mn>0</mn> </msub><mo>)</mo></mrow></math></formula>. In the case where <formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><mi>p</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>&infin;</mi></mrow></math></formula>,
Problems <formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><mo>(</mo><msup><mi>P</mi> <mo>&apos;</mo> </msup><mo>)</mo></mrow></math></formula> and <formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><mo>(</mo><msup><mi>P</mi> <mrow><mo>&apos;</mo><mo>&apos;</mo><mo>&apos;</mo></mrow> </msup><mo>)</mo></mrow></math></formula> can viewed as special cases of
<formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>P</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></math></formula> and <formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><mo>(</mo><msup><mi>P</mi> <mrow><mo>&apos;</mo><mo>&apos;</mo></mrow> </msup><mo>)</mo></mrow></math></formula> respectively, but if <formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><mi>p</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mi>&infin;</mi></mrow></math></formula> the situation
is different.</p>
<p>where the constraint on the approximant is expressed in terms of
its real and imaginary parts while the criterion takes only its real part
into account:</p>
<p><hi rend='slanted'>Let <formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><mi>p</mi><mo>&ge;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></math></formula>, <formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mi>K</mi></math></formula> be an arc of the unit circle <formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mi>T</mi></math></formula>,
<formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo>&Element;</mo><msup><mi>L</mi> <mi>p</mi> </msup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>K</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow></math></formula>, <formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><mi>&psi;</mi><mo>&Element;</mo><msup><mi>L</mi> <mi>p</mi> </msup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>T</mi><mo>&setminus;</mo><mi>K</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow></math></formula>, and <formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><mi>&alpha;</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>&beta;</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>M</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></math></formula>;
find a function <formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><mi>g</mi><mo>&Element;</mo><msup><mi>H</mi> <mi>p</mi> </msup></mrow></math></formula> such that
<formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>&alpha;</mi><mspace width='0.166667em'/><mo>&parallel;</mo><mtext>Re</mtext><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><mi>g</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>&psi;</mi></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><mo>&parallel;</mo></mrow> <mrow><msup><mi>L</mi> <mi>p</mi> </msup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>T</mi><mo>&setminus;</mo><mi>K</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow> </msub><mo>+</mo><mi>&beta;</mi><mspace width='0.166667em'/><msub><mrow><mo>&parallel;</mo><mtext>Im</mtext><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><mi>g</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>&psi;</mi></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><mo>&parallel;</mo></mrow> <mrow><msup><mi>L</mi> <mi>p</mi> </msup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>T</mi><mo>&setminus;</mo><mi>K</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow> </msub><mo>&le;</mo><mi>M</mi></mrow></math></formula> and
such that <formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><mtext>Re</mtext><mo>(</mo><mi>g</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>f</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></math></formula> is of minimal norm in <formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><msup><mi>L</mi> <mi>p</mi> </msup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>K</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow></math></formula>
under this constraint.</hi></p>
<p>see sections <ref target='uid29'/> and
<ref target='uid45'/>, where data and physical prior
information concern real (or imaginary) parts of analytic functions.</p>
<p>This allows one to</p>
<list type='ordered'>
<item id-text='1' id='uid15' label='(1)'><p noindent='true'>extend the index theorem to the case <formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>&le;</mo><mi>p</mi><mo>&le;</mo><mi>&infin;</mi></mrow></math></formula></p>
</item>
<item id-text='2' id='uid16' label='(2)'><p noindent='true'>study asymptotic errors with</p>
</item>
<item id-text='3' id='uid17' label='(3)'><p noindent='true'>characterize the asymptotic (cf. section <ref target='uid38'/>).</p>
</item></list>
<p>In connection with the second and third items above,see section <ref target='uid46'/>.</p>
</div2>
<div2 id-text='2' id='uid18'><head>Scalar rational approximation</head>
<participants><pers prenom='Laurent' nom='Baratchart'/>
<pers prenom='Martine' nom='Olivi'/>
<pers prenom='Edward' nom='Saff'/>
<pers prenom='Herbert' nom='Stahl'>TFH Berlin</pers>
<pers prenom='Maxim' nom='Yattselev'/>
</participants>
<keywords>
<term>rational approximation</term>
<term>critical point</term>
<term>orthogonal polynomials</term>
</keywords><p>Rational approximation is the second step mentioned
in section <ref target='uid12'/>.
The Problem can be stated as:</p>
<p><hi rend='slanted'>Let <formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>&le;</mo><mi>p</mi><mo>&le;</mo><mi>&infin;</mi></mrow></math></formula>, <formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo>&Element;</mo><msup><mi>H</mi> <mi>p</mi> </msup></mrow></math></formula> and <formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mi>n</mi></math></formula> an integer;
find a rational function without poles in the unit disk, and of
degree at most <formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mi>n</mi></math></formula> that is nearest possible to <formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><mi>f</mi></math></formula> in <formula type='inline'><math xmlns='http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML'><msup><mi>H</mi> <mi>p</mi> </msup></math></formula>.</hi>
In this way we are led to consider
minimizing a criterion of the form:</p>
